text_caption: It‚Äôs crazy that before becoming a parent I was able to just go about life not thinking about much more than myself. Day to day I didn‚Äôt have anyone I needed to rush home to urgently. I didn‚Äôt feel a sense of guilt for not constantly being around. Now even if I leave for an hour or 30 minutes there is this deep pull to rush home. I forget what it feels like to not feel like I‚Äôm in a rush. Mom guilt is real and I truly thought I wouldn‚Äôt have it. That was silly of me. And yet I still wouldn‚Äôt trade it for the world. The best reason to rush. We have a changing pad, a nursing cover, and a swaddle blanket just in case. A couple of burp cloths and bibs for spit up. A change of clothes with a cute little hat. I love these booties and some socks. I love this portable sound machine by Hatch. I also use a small pouch and pack a few things for myself like a hand sanitizer, a lotion stain remover. Just some things to have on hand with me. I also make sure to always bring a pacifier. I just have it attached to the side of the diaper bag.

text_transcription: are four ways that you can prevent diaper dermatitis in a newborn with a big thank you to Pampers for sponsoring this post. I'm an OB-GYN, so I spend a lot of time with my recently postpartum patients and their babies. I'm also a mom of three, so I've spent a lot of time diapering. Did you know that more than 70% of newborns will develop diaper dermatitis? Here are the four things that you can do to help prevent this. Number one, routinely exposing your baby's bottom to air. Number two, use pH balance wipes to gently tap on their skin instead of pulling across their skin. Number three, use a thick layer of diaper cream. And number four, use super absorbent disposable diapers. Pampers diapers and wipes are designed with seven skin protecting features, including an absorbent core and a barrier ointment. They also have a soft fabric on the outside and the inside to help stop any irritation on all sides of the diaper. There are many reasons why this is the number one choice of hospitals, parents, and nurses. When given so many options for diapers, choose the one that pediatricians have recommended for over 60 years.

From receiving a hand to extending a hand, meet Emma, a P&G employee and volunteer at Lifted Hands community pantry in Moorefield, West Virginia. text_transcription: I grew up in West Virginia. I was raised by my dad. We struggled quite a bit growing up. Probably over half of the year, we did rely on state services. We relied on pantries. Seeing and dealing with that firsthand is probably one of the things that drove me so hard into community service. I don't want anybody else to have to struggle if there's something that I can do about it. I started working with P&G almost six years ago. I started as a plant technician on the lines making all of our products. P&G has a donation program. Lifted Hands is the food bank here in Moorfield. I'm a Jean and the girls that run the pantry are really, really amazing at helping anybody that needs help. The first I reached out to Emma was probably about a year and a half ago. She knows the area, so that worked really well for her and I, and she has been such a blessing. The most requested items that we get is toilet paper, paper towels, pampers. To get that stuff is a blessing to some of these people, especially the ones who have children. This is an awesome program. Emma Jean does a wonderful job. She's always supporting people and helping people. She said anything I need, anytime she let me come and get it. I work with a lot of partners at P&G. It's not a one-man crew. I met Emma at P&G. It wasn't until she joined my United Way committee that I immediately knew she was going to be one of my best friends ever. I have been volunteering through P&G's United Way committee since 2018 when I first started. We do a lot of different things. P&G, they do a really good job at hiring people to take care of the community. P&G, I 100% see myself and many, many, many of the people that we help here. And anything that I can do to lessen somebody else's struggle, I'm going to do everything in my power to try to help. P&G anxiety, remember just over and over again. than to leave P&G...

text_transcription: Did you know that using the wrong diaper can cause diaper rash? That's exactly why I recommend Pampers to help protect against four of the main causes of diaper rash. Wet skin is three times more susceptible to irritation from friction, and if you add rough diaper materials on an active baby, you've got diaper rash. Poop contains irritants that cause inflammation, and if it sits against your baby's skin, the skin barrier is compromised, which can lead to diaper rash. Moisture trapped against the skin sets the perfect stage for rash to develop, and most parents don't know this, but what we use to wipe baby's skin can actually change their pH to a level that makes diaper rash more likely. Pampers' unique technology helps protect against four of the main causes of diaper rash so parents have one less thing to worry about.

text_transcription: Did you know that using the wrong diaper can cause diaper rash? That's exactly why I recommend Pampers to help protect against four of the main causes of diaper rash. Wet skin is three times more susceptible to irritation from friction, and if you add rough diaper materials on an active baby, you've got diaper rash. Poop contains irritants that cause inflammation, and if it sits against your baby's skin, the skin barrier is compromised, which can lead to diaper rash. Moisture trapped against the skin sets the perfect stage for rash to develop, and most parents don't know this, but what we use to wipe baby's skin can actually change their pH to a level that makes diaper rash more likely. Pampers' unique technology helps protect against four of the main causes of diaper rash so parents have one less thing to worry about.

text_transcription: are four ways that you can prevent diaper dermatitis in a newborn with a big thank you to Pampers for sponsoring this post. I'm an OB-GYN, so I spend a lot of time with my recently postpartum patients and their babies. I'm also a mom of three, so I've spent a lot of time diapering. Did you know that more than 70% of newborns will develop diaper dermatitis? Here are the four things that you can do to help prevent this. Number one, routinely exposing your baby's bottom to air. Number two, use pH balance wipes to gently tap on their skin instead of pulling across their skin. Number three, use a thick layer of diaper cream. And number four, use super absorbent disposable diapers. Pampers diapers and wipes are designed with seven skin protecting features, including an absorbent core and a barrier ointment. They also have a soft fabric on the outside and the inside to help stop any irritation on all sides of the diaper. There are many reasons why this is the number one choice of hospitals, parents, and nurses. When given so many options for diapers, choose the one that pediatricians have recommended for over 60 years.

text_transcription: Did you know that using the wrong diaper can cause diaper rash? That's exactly why I recommend Pampers to help protect against four of the main causes of diaper rash. Wet skin is three times more susceptible to irritation from friction, and if you add rough diaper materials on an active baby, you've got diaper rash. Poop contains irritants that cause inflammation, and if it sits against your baby's skin, the skin barrier is compromised, which can lead to diaper rash. Moisture trapped against the skin sets the perfect stage for rash to develop, and most parents don't know this, but what we use to wipe baby's skin can actually change their pH to a level that makes diaper rash more likely. Pampers' unique technology helps protect against four of the main causes of diaper rash so parents have one less thing to worry about.
